            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/1118354/" class=" " title="veteran">veteran</a>
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="31669880">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">
p54，而不适于在讨论英国特定时期中现实的舆论潮流与现实的立法之间关系的讲座上进行讲授。&quot;后面一句“may be dismissed from our consideration.&quot;没有翻译出来。这段虽然有些修辞没翻译出来，不过中文意思还是清楚的。</span>
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/31669880/">(<span class="">1回应</span>)</a>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2014-05-20 18:00</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                
p54，而不适于在讨论英国特定时期中现实的舆论潮流与现实的立法之间关系的讲座上进行讲授。&quot;后面一句“may be dismissed from our consideration.&quot;没有翻译出来。这段虽然有些修辞没翻译出来，不过中文意思还是清楚的。
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







<div class="rec-sec">

    <span class="rec">

<a href="https://www.douban.com/accounts/register?reason=collect" class="j a_show_login lnk-sharing lnk-douban-sharing">推荐</a>
</span>
</div>

                  </div>
                <div class="pl col-time">
                  <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/31669880/#comments">1回应</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
                  2014-05-20 18:00
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      
      <li class="ctsh clearfix" data-cid="31655033">
        <div class="ilst">
          <a href="https://www.douban.com/people/1118354/"><img src="https://img1.doubanio.com/icon/u1118354-19.jpg" alt="veteran" class="" /></a>
        </div>
        <div class="con">
          <div class="nlst">
            <h3>
              <div class="note-toggle rr">
                <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/31655033/" class="note-unfolder">展开</a>
                <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="note-folder">收起</a>
              </div>
              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/31655033/" class="">第48页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/1118354/" class=" " title="veteran">veteran</a>
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="31655033">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">
This conclusion, however, though roughly true, cannot be accepted
without considerable reservation.
然而，尽管粗略正确，这个结论不能未加深思熟虑的保留而被接纳。

The sovereign power may hold that a
certain kind of legislation is in itself expedient, but may at the same time
be unwilling, or even unable, to carry this conviction into effect, and this
from the dread of offending the feeling...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2014-05-19 15:56</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                
This conclusion, however, though roughly true, cannot be accepted<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>without considerable reservation.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>然而，尽管粗略正确，这个结论不能未加深思熟虑的保留而被接纳。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The sovereign power may hold that a<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>certain kind of legislation is in itself expedient, but may at the same time<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>be unwilling, or even unable, to carry this conviction into effect, and this<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>from the dread of offending the feelings of subjects who, though they in<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>general take no active share in public affairs, may raise an insuperable<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>opposition to laws which disturb their habits or shock their moral sentiment;<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>it is well indeed, thus early in these lectures, to note that the public<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>opinion which finds expression in legislation is a very complex phenomenon,<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>and often takes the form of a compromise resulting from a conflict<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>between the ideas of the government and the feelings or habits of the<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>governed.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>统治权也许会主张某种特定类型的立法处于自身的立法权宜之中，但同时也许是不情愿的，甚或是无能力做出有效的说服，这出自缺失对公众立法情感的抗辩，尽管公众一般并不积极地参与公共事务，他们也许会对法律提出一种非常强硬的反对意见，认为那些法律搅扰了他们的习惯或者撼动了他们的道德情感。因此在这些讲座初期，需要确实指出的是，立法过程中的公共舆论是一种非常复杂的现象，并且常常产生自一种冲突后果的妥协，这种冲突发生在政府理念和被统治者的情感或习惯之间。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>This holds good in all countries, whatever be their form of government,<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>but is more manifest than elsewhere in a country such as England,<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>where the legislation enacted by Parliament constantly bears traces<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>of the compromise arrived at between enlightenment and prejudice.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>这一点在所有邦国都是有效的，无论他们的政府类型。但是比起其他邦国，英国更为明显，在这里，议会的立法过程持久承载着来自偏见和理智之间妥协的踪迹。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The failure of Parliament during the eighteenth century to introduce reasonable<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>reforms, for instance, was due far less to the prejudices of members of<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Parliament, or even of the electorate, than to the deference which statesmen<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>instinctively, and on the whole wisely, paid to the dulness or stupidity of<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Englishmen, many of whom had no votes, and were certainly not able to<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>dictate by constitutional means to Parliament.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>例如，十八世纪议会朝着理性化改革失败的原因，并非归于议会成员甚或选民的偏见的影响，而是政治家们本能地或整体明智地为英国国民的迟钝或愚蠢买单。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Walpole and his Whig associates<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>were utterly free from bigotry, yet Walpole would never consent<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>to relieve Dissenters from the Test Act, though Dissenters were his most<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>strenuous supporters. The Act facilitating the naturalisation of Jews was,<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>in obedience to popular clamour, repealed in the next session after it had been passed. Even the amendment of the calendar was found to be a matter<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>of great difficulty; the ignorance of the electors was imposed upon by the<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>phrase that they had been robbed of eleven days.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>瓦尔坡尔和他的辉格盟友们曾完全抛弃宗教偏见，然而他绝不会认同让独立派们豁免自《宗教考验法》，尽管独立派曾是他最稳固的支持者。这种为犹太人归化提供便利的法案曾在它通过的第二季遭到废除，迫于公共呼声。即使日历的修订也是非常困难的一件事：作用于选民无知的是，他们认为修订的日历导致一年被掠夺了11天。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The moderate measure<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>of 1778 for the mitigation of the penal laws against Roman Catholics gave<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>rise in 1780 to an outbreak of revolutionary violence; and the Lord George<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Gordon Riots explain, if they do not justify, the long delay of Catholic<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Emancipation. But the Roman Catholic Relief Act of 1829 is itself the most<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>striking monument of legislative compromise. The measure was carried by<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>reformers who desired the removal of all the political disabilities under<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>which the Roman Catholics of the United Kingdom suffered, but it contains<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>stringent provisions on the face of them intended to banish from the<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>United Kingdom “every Jesuit and every member of any other religious<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>order, community, or society of the Church of Rome bound by monastic<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>or religious vows.”<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1778年，旨在减缓对罗马天主教徒的刑事制裁的审慎法案，在1780年引发了一场革命性的暴力冲突，并且暴动领袖乔治.戈登解释道，如果他们不修订那些法案，将会导致天主教解放的更长期的耽搁。但是1892年的罗马天主教豁免法案本身就是立法妥协的最卓著的丰碑。这项法案由那些改革者们所施行，他们意欲除去所有被赦免的英帝国治下的罗马天主教徒的政治歧视，但是它包含了一些严厉的条款，这些条款表面上试图从英帝国废除政治歧视，“每一个耶稣会信徒和其他任何一个宗教法令、团体，或被僧侣或宗教誓约界定的罗马天主教组织”<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>How does it happen that a law restoring to Roman<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Catholics the rights of citizenship, contained penal laws against Jesuits and<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>monks? The answer lies close at hand. The general scope of the Act represents<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>the enlightenment of a governing class which, by favour of peculiar<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>circumstances, carried through a scheme of religious toleration opposed<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>to the prejudices of the people. Penal enactments threatening Jesuits and<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>monks with a banishment, which had never in a single instance been put<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>in force, are the monument of a concession made by parliamentary statesmanship<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>to vulgar bigotry.4<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>这是何以发生的，当一个旨在保障罗马天主教徒公民权利的法案，也包含着反对耶稣会信徒和僧侣的刑事制裁律令？答案是明显的。这种法案的通常视野呈现出一个统治性阶层的明智，处于特别的环境需要，他们制定法律，采取了一种和民众偏见相对的宗教宽容的设计。旨在威慑耶稣会信徒和僧侣的刑罚法令，本身也拥有一种废除威慑的特性，因此该法令从来没有被执行过，这项法令是有关议会政治家原则向民众粗俗偏见妥协让步的丰碑。
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







<div class="rec-sec">

    <span class="rec">

<a href="https://www.douban.com/accounts/register?reason=collect" class="j a_show_login lnk-sharing lnk-douban-sharing">推荐</a>
</span>
</div>

